<subSubSection pageId="129" pageNumber="526" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="129.[1427,2634,1636,2536]" pageId="129" pageNumber="526">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1428,1774,2305,2338]" pageId="129" pageNumber="526">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Not assessed on The IUCN Red List. The Fingui White-toothed Shrew was recently recognition as a species. It is known only from a few recent specimens and one older specimen, but it is considered common by local people. It might occur in Obo Natural Park. Additional research is needed, but it is not affected by human habitation and plantations.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
